Dutch filmmaker Theo van Gogh, known for his controversial film on Islam, was tragically shot and stabbed to death in Amsterdam.
Despite receiving death threats, he refused police protection.
The murder sparked condemnation and calls for calm from Dutch officials and Muslim organizations.
The suspect, with ties to Islamic extremists, was arrested after a shootout.
Van Gogh's provocative views on Islam stirred controversy, but freedom of speech was defended.
The tragic event highlighted tensions in the Netherlands, with fears of ethnic unrest.
The suspect's radical Islamic beliefs were cited as the motive for the heinous act.
